<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="122" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1350,1951]" pageId="4" pageNumber="122">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1782,1807]" pageId="4" pageNumber="122">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Distant" authorityName="Distant" box="[629,887,1782,1807]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Drabescus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="122" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="conspicuus">
<emphasis box="[629,793,1784,1807]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="122">D. conspicuus</emphasis>
Distant
</taxonomicName>
, but can be distinguished by its apically broad pygofer side, more slender and elongate aedeagal shaft with longer basal processes and basal margin slightly sinuate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="123" pageId="4" pageNumber="122" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1350,1951]" pageId="4" pageNumber="122">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1890,1915]" pageId="4" pageNumber="122">Etymology.</emphasis>
New species name is derived from the Latin word “ 
<taxonomicName box="[923,1044,1891,1915]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Drabescus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="122" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="convolutus">
<emphasis box="[923,1044,1891,1915]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="122">convolutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
”, referring to the inwardly twisted apex of the pygofer side.
</paragraph>
